{"parse":{"title":"Risk inclination formula","pageid":38740974,"revid":824453462,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>risk inclination formula</b> uses the principle of moments, or <a href=\"/wiki/Varignon%27s_theorem_(mechanics)\" title=\"Varignon&#39;s theorem (mechanics)\">Varignon\u2019s theorem</a>, <sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> to calculate the first <a href=\"/wiki/Factorial_moment\" title=\"Factorial moment\">factorial moment</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Probability\" title=\"Probability\">probability</a> in order to define this center point of balance among all <a href=\"/wiki/Confidence_weighting\" title=\"Confidence weighting\">confidence weights</a> (i.e., the point of risk equilibration).\n</p><p>The formal derivation of the RIF is divided into three separate calculations: (1) calculation of 1st factorial moment, (2) calculation of inclination, and (3) calculation of the risk inclination score.\n</p><p>The RIF <sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> is a component of the <a href=\"/wiki/Risk_inclination_model\" title=\"Risk inclination model\">risk inclination model</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Risk_inclination_formula&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\n<cite class=\"citation book\">Coxeter, H. S. M. (1967). <i>Quadrangles: Varignon's Theorem. Geometry Revisited</i>. Washington, D.C.: The Mathematical Association of America. pp.&#160;51\u201355.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Quadrangles%3A+Varignon%27s+Theorem.+Geometry+Revisited&amp;rft.place=Washington%2C+D.C.&amp;rft.pages=51-55&amp;rft.pub=The+Mathematical+Association+of+America&amp;rft.date=1967&amp;rft.aulast=Coxeter&amp;rft.aufirst=H.+S.+M.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARisk+inclination+formula\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">\n<cite class=\"citation book\">Sharma, D. P. (2010). <i>Engineering Mechanics</i>. New Delhi, India: Dorling Kindersley. pp.&#160;8\u20139.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Engineering+Mechanics&amp;rft.place=New+Delhi%2C+India&amp;rft.pages=8-9&amp;rft.pub=Dorling+Kindersley&amp;rft.date=2010&amp;rft.aulast=Sharma&amp;rft.aufirst=D.+P.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARisk+inclination+formula\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation conference\">Jack, B.M.; Hung, K.M.; Liu, C.J.; Chiu, H.L. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.eric.ed.gov/ERICWebPortal/search/recordDetails.jsp?searchtype=basic&amp;pageSize=10&amp;ERICExtSearch_Facet_0=facet_au&amp;ERICExtSearch_SearchValue_0=Brady+Michael+Jack&amp;ERICExtSearch_FacetValue_0=%22Jack%2C+Brady%22&amp;ERICExtSearch_SearchType_0=au&amp;_pageLabel=RecordDetails&amp;objectId=0900019b8046c889&amp;accno=ED519174&amp;_nfls=false\"><i>Utilitarian Model of Confidence Testing for K